Data Preprocessing Exercise 2

Review of World Health Organization’s Life Expectancy Data taken from Kaggle.

String processing

Status is character class but it should be a factor. Let’s convert it.

str(data$Status)
##  chr [1:2938] "Developing" "Developing" "Developing" "Developing" ...
data$Status = as.factor(data$Status)
class(data$Status)

Because of the high number of Hepatitis B cases missing, we will remove this column from our dataset. Our research questions do not pertain to Hepatitis.

data = subset(data,select = -c(`Hepatitis B`))

Because there is such a high occurence of missing Population data,we will merge in the gapminder dataset and match on coutnry and year.

suppressPackageStartupMessages(require(gapminder))
## Warning: package 'gapminder' was built under R version 3.5.3
data2 <- inner_join(data, gapminder, by = c("Year" = "year", "Country" = "country"))
## Warning: Column `Country`/`country` joining character vector and factor,
## coercing into character vector
data2 = merge(x=data, y=gapminder, by.x = c("Year", "Country"), by.y = c("year", "country"))
# test how well new and old pop are correlated (should be extremely high)
data2$pop = as.numeric(data2$pop)
data_na_rm = na.omit(data2)
cor(data_na_rm$Population, data_na_rm$pop)
## [1] 0.4612533
plot(data_na_rm$Population, data_na_rm$pop)

It looks like the original data has some scaling issues of their population variable. Gapminder is consistent, so we will use pop from there and omit Population.

data2 = subset(data2, select = -`Population`)

What about GDP?

cor(data_na_rm$GDP, data_na_rm$gdpPercap)
## [1] 0.7956505
plot(data_na_rm$GDP, data_na_rm$gdpPercap)

It seems like the original GDP data is country GDP whereas gdpPercap is of course per capita. We will not omit GDP as it is different data, but probably we will rely on gdpPercap.

What about Life Expectancy?

cor(data_na_rm$`Life expectancy`, data_na_rm$lifeExp)
## [1] 0.9679432
plot(data_na_rm$`Life expectancy`, data_na_rm$lifeExp)

The correlation is high and it looks like any values changed within the gapminder data are within the margin of error. Since our main data source is Life Expectancy (WHO), we will keep their life expectancy varaible and drop gapminder.

data2 = subset(data2, select = -`lifeExp`)

scaling and normalization

Most of our variables are zero inflated and/or right skewed. Let’s take a few (infant deaths, GDP, Diphtheria) and normalize and scale them.

Z-Score scaling of infant deaths

hist(data2$`infant deaths`)

zscore = function(x){return((x-mean(x))/(sd(x)))}
data2$infant_scaled = zscore(data2$`infant deaths`)
data2 %>% select(`infant deaths`, infant_scaled) %>% head()
##   infant deaths infant_scaled
## 1            88     0.2797023
## 2             1    -0.2742819
## 3            20    -0.1532968
## 4            96     0.3306433
## 5            12    -0.2042379
## 6             1    -0.2742819
plot(density(data2$`infant deaths`))

plot(density(data2$infant_scaled))

Normalization of GDP Per Capita

hist(data2$GDP)

discretizing variables

Let’s create a discretized version of Life Expectancy using clustering.

set.seed(1)
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(sampling))
## Warning: package 'sampling' was built under R version 3.5.3
s <- kmeans(data2$`Life expectancy`, 3)

data2$lifecluster <- factor(s$cluster, labels = c(`1` = 'young', `2` = 'middle',`3` = 'high'), ordered = TRUE)
plot(data2$`Life expectancy`, data2$lifecluster)

  1. Do you have numerical attributes that you might want to discretize? Try at least two methods and compare the differences.

Life Expectancy can be discretized,

Categorical classification of low, med, and high of Life Expectancy rates using 3 cuts

data2$category <- cut(data2$`Life expectancy`, 
                              breaks = 3, 
                              labels=c('young', 'middle', 'high'))
dplyr::glimpse(data2$category)
##  Factor w/ 3 levels "young","middle",..: 1 2 2 1 3 3 3 3 2 3 ...

earlier we binned life expectancy using clusters with the following code:

set.seed(1)
suppressPackageStartupMessages(library(sampling))
s <- kmeans(data2$`Life expectancy`, 3)

data2$lifecluster <- factor(s$cluster, labels = c(`1` = 'young', `2` = 'middle',`3` = 'high'), ordered = TRUE)


dplyr::glimpse(data2$lifecluster)
summary(data2$lifecluster)

Since we binned using two different methods, let’s see how these methods compare in their binning.

ggplot(data2, aes(`Life expectancy`, y = value, color = variable)) + 
    geom_point(aes(y = category, col = "cut")) + 
    geom_point(aes(y = lifecluster, col = "cluster"))
